</div>
</section>

{{! ----- local_nida translation ----- }}
<section id="plugin-nida">
<h3>local_nida — submission &amp; feedback translation <span class="badge bg-secondary">v2.7.0</span></h3>

<p><code>local_nida</code> teaches the grader to work across a language barrier:
it renders a machine <strong>translation of a non-English submission</strong> for
the marker, and translates the marker's <strong>feedback back into the student's
language</strong>. It is opt-in per course — an admin enables the course and
picks its target languages — and when it isn't installed, or a course isn't
enabled, every hook below degrades silently and grading is unchanged.</p>

<h4>Translation panel (what the grader sees)</h4>
<p>For an assignment whose submission isn't in English, the preview pane gains a
translation view driven by
<code>local_unifiedgrader_get_submission_translation</code>:</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>English translation</strong> of the online text and each extractable file, shown alongside the original. A <em>machine-translation advisory</em> pill and a <em>mixed-language</em> warning make the provenance explicit; a <em>side-by-side (parallel)</em> sub-mode aligns source and translation segment by segment.</li>
    <li><strong>Submission-language badge.</strong> nida detects the language and the marker can confirm or override it (<code>local_unifiedgrader_confirm_student_language</code>) so feedback is translated back into the right language. The override list is the course's target languages plus English; when the detected language isn't one of them (e.g. French in a course that doesn't target it) the selector leads with a disabled placeholder showing the detected code rather than silently pre-selecting English.</li>
    <li><strong>Audio dub.</strong> When the submission embeds recorder audio, the panel can play a machine-generated <em>English dub</em> of it (grader-only, advisory).</li>
</ul>

<h4>Over-the-page segment comments</h4>
<p>Beyond whole-submission feedback, a marker can comment on an individual
<em>phrase</em> of the submission text. Each comment is anchored to a source
segment server-side — resolved against nida's aligned source <em>by hash</em>, so
no segment identifier is ever trusted from the browser — via
<code>local_unifiedgrader_save_segment_comment</code>. On the student's feedback
page every segment comment is rendered in the viewer's own language.</p>

<h4>Translated feedback for the student</h4>
<p>On the student feedback view, feedback reaches the student in their language
across every channel:</p>
<ul>
    <li>Overall feedback, rubric and marking-guide remarks flow through <code>format_text()</code> and are swapped automatically by the nida filter.</li>
    <li>PDF-annotation text bypasses <code>format_text()</code>, so it's delivered as a page-keyed translated list built by <code>feedback_data_helper::build_annotation_translations()</code>.</li>
    <li>Segment comments are translated and resolved from the nida store by hash (<code>build_segment_comment_translations()</code>).</li>
    <li>A <em>translation-pending</em> indicator shows while nida is still translating a channel (<code>feedback_api::get_feedback_status()</code>), so a half-translated page is never presented as final.</li>
</ul>

<h4>How the integration works</h4>
<ul>
    <li>Course targets come from <code>local_nida</code>'s <em>enabled courses</em> allowlist; <code>grade.php</code> passes the course's languages to the panel, and the feedback page reads the viewer's language via <code>current_language()</code>.</li>
    <li>Every hook is <code>class_exists()</code> / <code>function_exists()</code>-gated and wrapped so a translation-subsystem failure can never break grading: the externals return a terminal <code>unavailable</code> / <code>saved=false</code>, and the panel hides itself on a terminal status or any AJAX error.</li>
    <li>Translated HTML is already <code>clean_text()</code>'d server-side by nida; the grader UI passes it through a second, independent <strong>client-side sanitiser</strong> before display as defence-in-depth.</li>
</ul>

<p>The plugin's own UI-string translations (Afrikaans, German, …) are a separate
concern — see <a href="#feature-i18n">Languages</a>.</p>

<div class="local-unifiedgrader-help-screenshot">
    <i class="fa fa-image" aria-hidden="true"></i>
    <span>Screenshot: the translation panel showing a non-English submission with
    its English translation side-by-side, the machine-translation advisory pill,
    and the submission-language badge with its confirm dropdown open.</span>
</div>
</section>

{{! ----- bbbext_advgrd ----- }}
<section id="plugin-advgrd">
<h3>bbbext_advgrd — BBB rubric / marking guide</h3>

<p>Adds an advanced-grading area (rubric or marking guide) to a
BigBlueButton activity. When installed and configured for a BBB
activity, the Unified Grader renders the rubric / marking guide in the
marking pane the same way assignment / forum rubrics are rendered.</p>

<h4>How the integration works</h4>
<ul>
    <li>The adapter calls <code>get_grading_manager($context, 'bbbext_advgrd', 'participation')</code> to detect the active method.</li>
    <li>Saves go through <code>\bbbext_advgrd\local\grader::record_grade</code>, which writes the per-user evidence snapshot to <code>bbbext_advgrd_grade</code>, pushes the score to the BBB gradebook item, and emits per-presence sub-scores in analytic mode.</li>
    <li>Metric-driven level suggestions (<code>grader::suggest_levels</code>) are sent to the marking pane in the grading-definition payload — the rubric UI <em>could</em> highlight recommended cells based on engagement metrics, though that final highlight UI is on the roadmap rather than shipped.</li>
    <li>The grading instance id is reused across saves (looked up from the previous <code>bbbext_advgrd_grade</code> row) so consecutive saves update the same fillings rather than minting a new <code>grading_instances</code> row each time.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Annotation overlay in the preview <span class="badge bg-secondary">v2.6.2</span></h4>
<p>When <code>bbbext_advgrd</code> exposes an annotation overlay for the student,
the Unified Grader renders it <em>in place of</em> the BBB recording iframe in
the preview and student feedback panes — an own-player with an engagement
timeline, per-moment comments, and an audio/video feedback callout. The coupling
is deliberately loose: the adapter probes
<code>mod/bigbluebuttonbn/extension/advgrd/lib.php</code> and calls
<code>bbbext_advgrd_render_overlay($cmid, $userid)</code> only if that function
exists, falling back to the standard iframe when the extension is absent or
returns nothing. The preview page buffers its body output so the extension's
editor / AMD head requirements land in <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> before the page
header is flushed, and the fullscreen control targets the overlay's
<code>.advgrd-player-wrapper</code> so fullscreen works on the embedded feedback
view too.</p>

<p>For full BBB context see <a href="#integration-bigbluebuttonbn">BigBlueButton</a>.
For general rubric / marking-guide UX see
<a href="#feature-rubrics">Marking guides &amp; rubrics</a>.</p>
</section>

{{! ----- quizaccess_duedate ----- }}
<section id="plugin-quizaccess-duedate">
<h3>quizaccess_duedate — per-user quiz extensions</h3>

<p>Provides a per-user / per-group due-date override system for quizzes,
filling a gap in Moodle core (which has open / close / cut-off but no
clean "extension" concept).</p>

<p>When installed, the Unified Grader:</p>
<ul>
    <li>Lets teachers grant and revoke extensions inline from the grader.</li>
    <li>Resolves the effective due date through <code>\quizaccess_duedate\override_manager::get_effective_duedate()</code> — user override &gt; group override &gt; quiz default — when checking lateness.</li>
    <li>Surfaces extensions in the unified <em>Overrides &amp; extensions</em> modal alongside Moodle's native <code>quiz_overrides</code>.</li>
</ul>

<p>Without the plugin, lateness falls back to <code>quiz.timeclose</code>
and the native <code>quiz_overrides</code> table.</p>

<p>This integration is checked at runtime via
<code>class_exists('\quizaccess_duedate\override_manager')</code> — no
configuration needed beyond installing the plugin.</p>
</section>

{{! ----- gradepenalty_duedate ----- }}
<section id="plugin-gradepenalty-duedate">
<h3>gradepenalty_duedate — automatic late penalties</h3>

<p>Computes a late-penalty percentage based on configurable rules
(per-module, per-course, or site-wide). The Unified Grader applies the
calculated deduction when pushing the grade to the gradebook.</p>

<ul>
    <li>For <strong>assignments</strong>, Moodle's own gradebook respects penalties; the integration surfaces the late badge with days-late count and percentage.</li>
    <li>For <strong>forums</strong>, the raw teacher-given grade is preserved in <code>forum_grades</code> and only the gradebook value is reduced. The plugin's <code>sync_gradebook_penalty()</code> step recalculates after extensions are granted, so granting an extension after grading correctly removes the penalty.</li>
    <li>For <strong>quizzes</strong>, penalty integration is disabled — quiz grades are computed by the question engine and percent-deducted penalties don't compose cleanly.</li>
</ul>

<p>Without the plugin, manual penalties (entered through the marking
panel) still work — they live in <code>local_unifiedgrader_penalty</code>
and are subtracted at gradebook-push time.</p>

<p>For UX details see <a href="#feature-penalties">Penalties</a>.</p>
</section>

{{! ----- Plagiarism plugins ----- }}
<section id="plugin-plagiarism">
<h3>Plagiarism plugins (Copyleaks, Turnitin, etc.)</h3>

<p>Any plugin returning HTML from Moodle's standard
<code>plagiarism_get_links()</code> API will integrate. The Unified
Grader doesn't talk to plagiarism vendors directly; it forwards the
submission item (post text, online-text submission, attached file) to
the API and renders whatever comes back.</p>

<h4>Plagiarism shield UX</h4>
<ul>
    <li>A small shield badge appears next to each submission item that has a non-empty plagiarism result.</li>
    <li>Colour-coded by severity — extracted from the plagiarism plugin's <em>own</em> CSS classes (e.g. <code>cls-plag-score-level-high</code>, <code>score_colour_75</code>) so it respects the plugin's configured thresholds rather than inventing new ones.</li>
    <li>Pending state (Copyleaks "scheduled" / "in-progress") and error state (Turnitin "queued" / Copyleaks "failed") render with appropriate icons.</li>
    <li>For Copyleaks, both the plagiarism score and the AI-content score contribute to the worst-severity colour.</li>
    <li>Click the shield to open a popout with the plagiarism plugin's full widget — match percentage, originality breakdown, etc. — and a click-through to the plugin's full report.</li>
</ul>

<p>On graded <strong>forums</strong>, per-attachment plagiarism reports are also
collected into the marking-panel <em>Plagiarism</em> card (post-body shields
keep rendering inline in the preview), so attachment results sit alongside the
grade without a duplicate display — the same card assignments use.</p>

<h4>Academic impropriety report &amp; referral</h4>
<p>If the admin has set <code>enable_report_form</code> +
<code>report_form_url</code>, the marking-panel <em>Plagiarism</em> card carries
a <em>Report academic impropriety</em> button. For markers with the
<code>local/unifiedgrader:refer</code> capability this is the <strong>combined
integrity control</strong>: one click flags the submission for review
<em>and</em> opens the report form (see <a href="#feature-referral">Academic-integrity
referral</a>). Markers without that capability get a plain link that just opens
the form. The form is a configurable external URL (e.g. a Microsoft / Google
Form or an LMS-internal workflow) whose template supports these placeholders:</p>

<ul>
    <li><code>{studentname}</code>, <code>{studentid}</code></li>
    <li><code>{coursecode}</code> (extracted via the configured regex), <code>{coursename}</code></li>
    <li><code>{activityname}</code>, <code>{activitytype}</code></li>
    <li><code>{gradername}</code>, <code>{graderurl}</code></li>
</ul>

<p>Without <code>$CFG->enableplagiarism</code> on, no shields appear and there
is no plagiarism card; the integrity button (for markers who can refer) then
falls back to the grade card.</p>
</section>

{{! ----- TinyMCE recorder ----- }}
<section id="plugin-tinymce-recorder">
<h3>TinyMCE recorder plugins</h3>

<p>The feedback editor is Moodle's preferred TinyMCE configuration.
Audio / video feedback recording is delegated to whichever TinyMCE
recorder plugin is installed:</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>RecordRTC</strong> (the standard Moodle plugin).</li>
    <li><strong>SATS Recorder</strong> (institution-specific TinyMCE plugin with cloud-storage backend).</li>
</ul>

<p>The Unified Grader doesn't ship its own recorder. The TinyMCE editor
is initialised once on page load and reused across student switches via
<code>editor.setContent()</code>; the recorder plugin (whichever is
present) attaches to that editor instance.</p>

<p>Recorded clips are uploaded to the editor's draft area and end up in
the <code>assignfeedback_comments</code> filearea on save — same path as
images / files inserted via the editor.</p>
</section>

</section>
